anings":["English: locative name from Riby (Lincs) or perhaps Ribby (Lancs); on the latter name,  see also  Rigby  . See also   Redmonds, Dictionary of Yorks Surnames  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Rigby","meanings":["English (Lancashire): habitational name from Ribby in Lancashire, named with Old Scandanavian <i>hryggr</i> ‘ridge’ + <i>bȳ</i> ‘farmstead, village’. Compare   Rigsby  ."]},{"name":"Redmonds, Dictionary of Yorks Surnames","meanings":["English: variant of   Bulcock  .   Redmonds, Dictionary of Yorks Surnames   notes that in the parish registers of Bolton by Bowland (WR Yorks) the same family name is spelled  <i>Bulcock</i>,  <i>Bowcocke</i>, and  <i>Boocock</i> (1608–30), and that Edward Bowcock of Howgill (WR Yorks) is also called Bulcock in a will dated 1677. Compare also Alice Bowcock, 1641, Chr. Bulcock, 1646 in   IGI   (Barnoldswick, WR Yorks)."]}]},{"name":"Simon","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Usual English form of   Simeon  , borne in the New Testament by various characters: two apostles, a brother of Jesus, a Pharisee, a leper, a tanner, a sorcerer (who offered money for the gifts of the Holy Ghost, giving rise to the term <i>simony</i>), and the man who carried Jesus's cross to the Crucifixion."],"variants":[{"name":"Simen","meanings":["Usual English form of   Simeon  , borne in the New Testament by various characters: two apostles, a brother of Jesus, a Pharisee, a leper, a tanner, a sorcerer (who offered money for the gifts of the Holy Ghost, giving rise to the term <i>simony</i>), and the man who carried Jesus's cross to the Crucifixion."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":40,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Simon Driby was born about 1175, in Driby, Lincolnshire, England, his father, Robert Driby, was 27 and his mother, Margaret Of Berkshire, was 23. He had at least 1 son with Mrs Simon Driby. He died after 1215, in Tumby, Lincolnshire, England."},"et":{"about 1175–after 1215":"umbes 1175–pärast 1215","1175–1215":"1175–1215","1175–Female":"1175–Surnud","1195–1245":"1195–1245","1150–Male":"1150–Surnud","1154–1194":"1154–1194","after 1215":"pärast 1215","Abt 1174":"umbes 1174","1215":"1215","1245":"1245","after 1194":"pärast 1194","1154":"1154","1175":"1175","1195":"1195","1194":"1194","1150":"1150","about 1175":"umbes 1175","Driby, Lincolnshire, England":"Driby, Lincolnshire, England","Wokefield, Stratfield Mortimer, Berkshire, England":"Stratfield Mortimer, Berkshire, England","Tumby, Lincolnshire, England":"Tumby, Lincolnshire, England"},"fi":{"about 1175–after 1215":"noin 1175–1215 jälkeen","1175–1215":"1175–1215","1175–Female":"1175–Kuollut","1195–1245":"1195–1245","1150–Male":"1150–Kuollut","1154–1194":"1154–1194","after 1215":"1215 jälkeen","Abt 1174":"noin 1174","1215":"1215","1245":"1245","after 1194":"1194 jälkeen","1154":"1154","1175":"1175","1195":"1195","1194":"1194","1150":"1150","about 1175":"noin 1175","Driby, Lincolnshire, England":"Driby, Lincolnshire, England","Wokefield, Stratfield Mortimer, Berkshire, England":"Stratfield Mortimer, Berkshire, England","Tumby, Lincolnshire, England":"Tumby, Lincolnshire, England"},"fr":{"about 1175–after 1215":"environ 1175–après 1215","1175–1215":"1175–1215","1175–Female":"1175–Décédée","1195–1245":"1195–1245","1150–Male":"1150–Décédé","1154–1194":"1154–1194","after 1215":"après 1215","Abt 1174":"environ 1174","1215":"1215","1245